{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638204"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:50:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:50:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17698"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17698"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10412"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72115"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10412"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17698"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57585"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10410"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24361"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72115"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESour taste perception is an important protective mechanism that helps organisms detect and avoid potentially harmful acidic substances.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of sour taste detection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sodium channel activation","G protein-coupled receptor activation","Direct cell membrane disruption","Calcium channel inhibition","Proton influx through ion channels"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe detection of sour taste primarily occurs through \u003Cstrong\u003Eproton influx through ion channels\u003C/strong\u003E. When acidic substances are present in the mouth, hydrogen ions enter taste receptor cells through acid-sensing ion channels (ASICs). Additionally, hydrogen ions block certain potassium channels. These actions lead to membrane depolarisation and neurotransmitter release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium channel activation\u003C/strong\u003E - Sodium channels play no specific role in sour taste detection, as the primary mechanism involves hydrogen ion channels.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EG protein-coupled receptor activation\u003C/strong\u003E - While this mechanism is important for sweet, bitter and umami tastes, sour taste detection relies on direct ion channel interactions.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect cell membrane disruption\u003C/strong\u003E - Sour taste is detected through specific ion channels rather than through non-specific membrane damage.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium channel inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E - Although calcium channels are involved in neurotransmitter release, they do not serve as primary sour taste detectors.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis mechanism allows for rapid and sensitive detection of acidic substances, which is crucial for avoiding potentially harmful foods.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sour taste is primarily detected by hydrogen ions (H+) interacting with specific ion channels on taste receptor cells.","The main ion channels involved in sour taste detection are acid-sensing ion channels (ASICs) and certain potassium channels.","Increased acidity leads to proton influx and potassium channel blockade, resulting in taste cell depolarisation."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57585"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17698"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57585"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:43:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:43:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10412"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72115"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4942"},"attributes":{"emoji"